# Nuxt 3 + Vue 3 + TypeScript Development Rules

## Core Principles
- Follow Nuxt 3 conventions and best practices
- Use TypeScript for type safety
- Prioritize performance and SEO
- Write clean, maintainable code
- Follow Vue 3 Composition API patterns

## Framework & Architecture
- Use Nuxt 3 with Vue 3 Composition API
- Leverage auto-imports for composables, components, and utilities
- Use server-side rendering (SSR) by default
- Implement proper error handling with error.vue pages
- Use Nuxt layers for code organization when needed

## File Structure & Naming
- Follow Nuxt 3 directory structure conventions
- Use kebab-case for file and directory names
- Component files: PascalCase (e.g., `MyComponent.vue`)
- Page files: kebab-case (e.g., `about-us.vue`)
- Composable files: camelCase with `use` prefix (e.g., `useAuth.ts`)
- Middleware files: kebab-case (e.g., `auth-guard.ts`)
- Plugin files: kebab-case with `.client` or `.server` suffix when needed

## Vue 3 & Composition API
- Always use `<script setup>` syntax
- Use `ref()` for reactive primitives, `reactive()` for objects
- Prefer `computed()` over methods for derived state
- Use `watch()` and `watchEffect()` appropriately
- Implement proper lifecycle hooks (`onMounted`, `onUnmounted`, etc.)
- Use `defineProps()` and `defineEmits()` for component communication
- Leverage `defineExpose()` when component methods need external access

## TypeScript Guidelines
- Use strict TypeScript configuration
- Define interfaces for all data structures
- Use generic types where appropriate
- Avoid `any` type - use `unknown` or proper typing
- Use type assertions sparingly and safely
- Define custom types in `types/` directory
- Use `Ref<T>` and `ComputedRef<T>` for reactive references

## State Management (Pinia)
- Use Pinia stores for global state management
- Define stores in `stores/` directory
- Use composition API style for stores
- Implement proper store organization (state, getters, actions)
- Use `storeToRefs()` when destructuring reactive store properties
- Handle async actions with proper error handling

## Directus Integration
- Use `nuxt-directus` module for CMS integration
- Implement proper authentication flows
- Use typed interfaces for Directus collections
- Handle API errors gracefully
- Implement proper caching strategies for CMS data
- Use `gql-query-builder` for complex GraphQL queries when needed

## Styling & UI (Reka UI)
- Use Reka UI components for consistent design
- Implement responsive design patterns
- Use CSS modules or scoped styles in components
- Follow accessibility best practices
- Use semantic HTML elements
- Implement proper color contrast and focus management

## Performance Optimization
- Use `lazy` loading for heavy components
- Implement proper image optimization with `@nuxt/image`
- Use `defineAsyncComponent()` for code splitting
- Leverage Nuxt's built-in performance features
- Implement proper caching strategies
- Use `useLazyFetch()` and `useLazyAsyncData()` for data fetching

## PWA Implementation
- Configure `@vite-pwa/nuxt` for offline functionality
- Implement proper service worker strategies
- Handle offline states gracefully
- Use proper manifest configuration
- Implement push notifications when needed

## Audio Integration (Howler.js)
- Use Howler.js for audio playback
- Implement proper audio loading states
- Handle audio permissions and autoplay policies
- Use composables for audio management
- Implement proper cleanup for audio resources

## Data Fetching Patterns
- Use `useFetch()` for client-side data fetching
- Use `$fetch()` for programmatic requests
- Implement proper loading and error states
- Use `refresh()` and `pending` from composables
- Handle server-side data requirements properly
- Use `navigateTo()` for programmatic navigation

## Error Handling
- Implement global error handling with error.vue
- Use try-catch blocks for async operations
- Provide meaningful error messages to users
- Log errors appropriately for debugging
- Handle network failures gracefully
- Use Nuxt's built-in error handling mechanisms

## SEO & Meta Management
- Use `useSeoMeta()` and `useHead()` for meta tags
- Implement proper Open Graph and Twitter Card tags
- Use structured data when appropriate
- Implement proper canonical URLs
- Handle dynamic meta tags based on content
- Use `definePageMeta()` for page-specific configuration

## Testing Guidelines
- Write unit tests for composables and utilities
- Use Vitest for testing framework
- Test component behavior, not implementation details
- Mock external dependencies appropriately
- Test error scenarios and edge cases
- Implement E2E tests for critical user flows

## Security Best Practices
- Sanitize user inputs
- Use HTTPS in production
- Implement proper CORS configuration
- Use environment variables for sensitive data
- Validate data on both client and server
- Implement proper authentication and authorization

## Code Quality
- Use ESLint with Nuxt configuration
- Follow consistent code formatting
- Write descriptive commit messages
- Use meaningful variable and function names
- Implement proper documentation for complex logic
- Remove unused imports and dead code

## Development Workflow
- Use pnpm for package management
- Follow semantic versioning
- Use feature branches for development
- Implement proper CI/CD pipelines
- Use environment-specific configurations
- Test thoroughly before deployment

## Common Patterns to Follow
```typescript
// Composable pattern
export const useMyFeature = () => {
  const state = ref(initialState)
  const computedValue = computed(() => transformation(state.value))
  
  const action = async () => {
    try {
      // async logic
    } catch (error) {
      // error handling
    }
  }
  
  return {
    state: readonly(state),
    computedValue,
    action
  }
}

// Component pattern
<script setup lang="ts">
interface Props {
  // Define props with proper types
}

const props = defineProps<Props>()
const emit = defineEmits<{
  action: [payload: PayloadType]
}>()

// Use composables
const { data, pending, error } = await useFetch('/api/data')
</script>
```

## Avoid These Patterns
- Don't use Options API - stick to Composition API
- Don't mix reactive and non-reactive data carelessly
- Don't ignore TypeScript errors
- Don't skip error handling in async operations
- Don't use inline styles - use proper CSS organization
- Don't forget to clean up watchers and listeners
- Don't ignore accessibility requirements

- Don't skip proper loading states for async operations